[
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text: "We will now learn more about the other types of pronouns"
      },
      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        styles: ["underline"],
        text: "Reflexive pronouns:"
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text:
          "These are used instead of an object pronoun when the object is the same person or thing as the subject. This is by adding self or selves to personal pronouns from them. The subject is the doer and receiver of the action"
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text:
          "Myself, yourself, themselves, ourself, ourselves, himself and herself"
      },
      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        text: "Examples:"
      },
      {
        type: "list",
        text: [
          "I cut myself while shaving.",
          "They built the house themselves.",
          "We tested the product ourselves."
        ]
      },

      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        styles: ["underline"],
        text: "Demonstrative Pronouns: "
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text:
          "They refer to the nouns for which they are used. These are used for things near or closely connected to the subject, or for things further away."
      },
      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        text: "Examples:"
      },
      {
        type: "list",
        text: [
          "This is my pen and that is yours.",
          "This is the same book, which I read sometime back.",
          "Did you complete that water storage project?"
        ]
      },

      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        styles: ["underline"],
        text: "Interrogative Pronouns"
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text: "They are used in questions – who, which, whose"
      },
      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        text: "Examples:"
      },
      {
        type: "list",
        text: [
          "Who is the thief?",
          "Which dish do you prefer?",
          "Whose design was selected?"
        ]
      },

      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        styles: ["underline"],
        text: "Relative Pronouns"
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text: "They refer to nouns mentioned before them."
      },
      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        text: "Examples:"
      },
      {
        type: "list",
        text: [
          "He is the boy who danced at the party.",
          "This is the bungalow, which my uncle has bought.",
          "This is our CEO, who has just returned from our head office in the USA."
        ]
      },

      {
        type: "TextTitle",
        styles: ["underline"],
        text: "Indefinite Pronouns"
      },
      {
        type: "paragraph",
        text:
          "These do not have any definite nouns. These are used to talk about people/things in a very general way, especially because we can’t or do not want to identify them."
