// Read

[
	{
		type: "slide",
		text: [
			{
				type: "title",
				text: "Adjectives"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Adjectives add information about the noun or pronoun it is modifying, such as its size, colour, shape, or other qualities."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "For example, in the sentence "The red apple is delicious," "red" is the adjective modifying the noun "apple." It provides additional information about the apple's colour."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "In English, the usual order is for the adjective to come before the noun, as in the example above. However, in some cases, the adjective comes after the noun, as in the woman, beautiful and kind."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				styles: ["italic"]
				text: "Sometimes we use multiple adjectives."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "You know it’s proper to say “pretty young girl” and wrong to say “young pretty girl”. There's a rule for this."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "<i>The rule is that multiple adjectives are always ranked accordingly: opinion, size, age, shape, colour, origin, material, purpose. Remember</i> <b>OSASCOMP.</b>"
			},
		]
	},
	{
		type: "slide",
		text: [
			{
				type: "title",
				text: "Degrees of comparison"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "When we want to compare two or more nouns using adjectives, we use the comparative and superlative forms of the adjective to show the comparison between the nouns."
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "For example,"
			},
			{
				type: "list",
				text: ["Jaggery is sweet, honey is sweeter but sugar is the sweetest."]
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "In this sentence, we are comparing the three nouns using the positive, comparative and superlative forms of the word ‘sweet’."
			},
			{
				type: "hr"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				styles: ["italic"]
				text: "Let’s learn more about these forms."
			},
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "Positive Form"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "These are the simple adjectives that describe the noun without comparing it to another."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Example - big, sweet, clean"
			},
			{
				type: "list",
				text: [
					"She has a <b>big</b> lunch bag.",
					"He is a <b>sweet</b> boy.",
					"The school is <b>clean.</b>"
				]
			},
			
			{
				type: "hr"
			},
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "Comparative Form"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "These are used when we are comparing two nouns and need to show which noun possesses the adjective or character in a greater or lesser amount, when compared with the other."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Example - bigger, sweeter, cleaner"
			},
			{
				type: "list",
				text: [
					"I have a big lunch bag but hers is <b>bigger</b>.",
					"He is <b>sweeter</b> than the other boys.",
					"The school is <b>cleaner</b> than before."
				]
			},
			
			{
				type: "hr"
			},
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "Superlative Form"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "This form is used when three or more nouns are being compared and we need to show that one or more of the nouns possess the adjective or characteristic to the highest amount possible. We usually add ‘the’ before the superlative form."
			},
			
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Example - biggest, sweetest, cleanest"
			},
			{
				type: "list",
				text: [
					"She has the <b>biggest</b> lunch bag in the class.",
					"He is the <b>sweetest</b> boy in his class.",
					"The school is the <b>cleanest</b> in the city."
				]
			},
			
			{
				type: "hr"
			},
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "Making Comparatives and Superlatives"
			},
			{
				type: "list",
				text: [
					"There are certain rules that must be followed in the making of the comparatives and superlatives of the adjectives.",
					"Not all adjectives form their comparatives and superlatives in the same way and there are also some irregular adjectives that form completely different comparative and superlative forms."
				]
			},
			
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "SINGLE SYLLABLE ADJECTIVES"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "We use ‘-er’ to make the comparative and ‘-est’ to make the superlative in small words."
			},
			{
				type: "table",
				text: {
					header: ["Positive", "Comparative", "Superlative"],
					rows: [
						["Tall","Taller","Tallest"],
						["Big", "Bigger", "Biggest"],
						["Hot", "Hotter", "Hottest"]
					]
				}
			},
			
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "TWO SYLLABLE ADJECTIVES"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Adjectives with two syllables can form the comparative either by adding ‘-er’ or by preceding the adjective with ‘more’. These adjectives form the superlative either by adding ‘-est’ or by preceding the adjective with ‘most’."
			},
			{
				type: "table",
				text: {
					header: ["Positive", "Comparative", "Superlative"],
					rows: [
						["Happy","Happier","Happiest"],
						["Famous", "<b>More</b> famous", "<b>Most</b> famous"],
						["Tangled", "<b>More</b> tangled", "<b>Most</b> tangled"]
					]
				}
			},
			
			
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "THREE OR MORE SYLLABLES"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "Adjectives with three or more syllables form the comparative by putting ‘more’ in front of the adjective, and the superlative by putting ‘most’ in front."
			},
			{
				type: "table",
				text: {
					header: ["Positive", "Comparative", "Superlative"],
					rows: [
						["Important", "<b>More</b> important", "<b>Most</b> important"],
						["Expensive", "<b>More</b> expensive", "<b>Most</b> expensive"]
					]
				}
			},
			
			{
				type: "title",
				styles: ["underline"],
				text: "IRREGULAR COMPARATIVES AND SUPERLATIVES"
			},
			{
				type: "paragraph",
				text: "The following very common adjectives have completely irregular comparative and superlative forms."
			},
			{
				type: "table",
				text: {
					header: ["Positive", "Comparative", "Superlative"],
					rows: [
